&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span&gt;Wellbeing Practitioner Trainee &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Children and Young Peoples Improving Access to Psychological Therapies (CYP IAPT)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Hours: One-year fixed-term training post. Full Time only (due to University course commitments).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Location: Shropshire – Telford and Shrewsbury.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;An exciting opportunity has arisen to recruit trainee Wellbeing practitioners to work in the Bee U service. This is a one-year fixed term training post in conjunction with the Children and Young People’s Improving Access to Psychological Therapies programme (CYP IAPT) delivered by Health Education England and partners that aims to improve existing children and young people’s mental health Services working in the community. Our trainee Well Being Practitioner for Children and Young People will be integrated with the Bee U service and linked to the CYP IAPT collaborative.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;This is a training role within the CYP IAPT programme and the post-holder will work within a Bee U as part of the multi-disciplinary team delivering, under supervision, high-quality; outcome –informed, focused, evidence-based interventions for children and young people experiencing, mild to moderate anxiety, low mood, behavioural difficulties &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;The training and service experience will equip the post holder with the necessary knowledge, attitude and capabilities to operate effectively in an inclusive, value driven service. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;The Wellbeing Practitioner course provides a thorough and robust theoretical base with particular focus on the protocols with the soundest evidence in low intensity interventions. In addition to providing practical, intensive and detailed skills training to facilitate skill development to a defined standard of competency, the course will aim to increase trainees’ knowledge base of theory and research in low intensity interventions and promote a critical approach to the subject. It will aim to equip trainees to become skilled, creative and independent Wellbeing practitioners who appropriately value and adhere to treatment protocols with fidelity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;This post includes both working with in the Bee U service and committing to all aspects of the Post-Graduate Diploma course run in collaboration with the University of Northampton. The post holder will be required to travel to and attend all taught university days utilise self-study days as required by the education provider, and specified within the agreed national curriculum. The remaining days of the week will be working with in the Bee U service using their newly developed skills. Applicants must be willing to travel&lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt; The successful candidates will be working as Trainee Wellbeing practitioner within the Bee U service for the duration of the one year course and would split their time between training and carrying out direct clinical work in service. After the fixed term training contract ends applicants would be encouraged to apply for any vacant posts within the services or local partner agencies. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;The clinical work involves being part of a multi-disciplinary team and successful candidates will carry their own caseload of Low intensity evidence based training cases. Workplace supervision will be provided weekly in addition to supervisory support at University.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Please note in this instance the course is not optional; there will be a joint interview with the University of Northampton / CYP IAPT Midlands collaborative to appoint to this role. The role is dependent on meeting all course requirements. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;All applicants will need to be available to start the training in January 2021&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;For further information please contact&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Sherryn Ravenscroft&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Sherryn.ravenscroft@mpft.nhs.uk&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;0300 124 0093 &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
